\f0\b\fs48 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 \uc0\u55358 \u56800  PART 1: DRIVE CONTROLLER (ARDUINO UNO)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The Arduino Uno is strictly responsible for handling the electronic speed controller (ESC), monitoring power consumption (Voltage/Amperage), driving the physical TM1637 LCD display, and managing hardware-level failsafes (like preventing the gears from stripping when shifting from forward to reverse).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 1. Hardware & Pin Definitions\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Pins 2 & 3:
\f1\b0  Connected to the TM1637 4-digit display (Clock and Data).\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Analog A0:
\f1\b0  Connected to a Current (Amperage) sensor.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Analog A1:
\f1\b0  Connected to a Voltage sensor via a voltage divider.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Pin 9:
\f1\b0  Generates the PWM signal for the motor's Electronic Speed Controller (ESC).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 2. Core Measurement Functions\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 getVolts()
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl1
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 What it does:
\f1\b0  Reads the raw analog value from pin A1 30 times and averages it to smooth out electrical noise.\
\ls2\ilvl1
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 How it works:
\f1\b0  It multiplies the raw value by the sensor's distance multiplier (
\f3\fs26 distV
\f1\fs24 ) and the hardware voltage divider ratio (
\f3\fs26 vDividerRatio
\f1\fs24 ). It then adds the software calibration offset (
\f3\fs26 v_offset
\f1\fs24 ) to ensure hyper-accurate readings.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 getAmps()
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl1
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 What it does:
\f1\b0  Calculates the live current draw of the motors.\
\ls2\ilvl1
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 How it works:
\f1\b0  It takes 100 rapid samples from pin A0. It compares this against the 
\f3\fs26 zeroPoint
\f1\fs24  (calibrated at boot). It calculates the difference, applies the sensor's sensitivity multiplier, and finally passes the result through an aggressive 
\f0\b Low-Pass Filter
\f1\b0  (
\f3\fs26 (currentAmps * 0.1) + (filteredAmps * 0.9)
\f1\fs24 ). This prevents the amperage spikes from looking jittery on the HUD.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 getBatteryPercentage()
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl1
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 What it does:
\f1\b0  Calculates a highly accurate, sag-corrected battery percentage that doesn't "bounce" around when driving.\
\ls2\ilvl1
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 How it works (The Ratchet Algorithm):
\f1\b0  1. It calculates 
\f4\i Voltage Sag
\f1\i0  by looking at the current Amps drawn divided by the number of parallel batteries. 2. It applies a heavy smoothing filter to the voltage to ignore sudden throttle punches. 3. It maps the voltage to a 0\'96100 scale depending on if you selected LiPo or NiMH in the settings. 4. 
\f0\b The Ratchet:
\f1\b0  It uses a variable called 
\f3\fs26 current_pct
\f1\fs24 . The code states: 
\f3\fs26 if (calc_pct < current_pct) current_pct = calc_pct;
\f1\fs24 . This means the battery percentage on the HUD can 
\f4\i only go down, never up
\f1\i0 . This prevents the battery from dropping to 40% under hard acceleration and bouncing back to 80% when you stop.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 3. Display & Animation Functions\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 scrollText(String text)
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl1
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 What it does:
\f1\b0  Creates a scrolling marquee effect on the 4-digit TM1637 display.\
\ls3\ilvl1
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 How it works:
\f1\b0  It pads the target text with spaces, converts standard characters into 7-segment hex codes, and shifts them across the 4 digits every 300 milliseconds. Used for displaying the IP address and Wi-Fi network name.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2\b\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 runAnimation()
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl1
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 What it does:
\f1\b0  Creates a circular spinning "loading" animation on the display when the drone has no Wi-Fi or IP address.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 4. Motor Control & Safety\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 applySmartBrakes()
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl1
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 What it does:
\f1\b0  Stops the drone rapidly instead of letting it coast.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 How it works:
\f1\b0  Standard ESCs coast when returning to neutral (1500ms pulse). If the drone was going forward (pulse > 1505), this function instantly blasts a full-reverse pulse (1000ms) for 350 milliseconds to brake the motor, then snaps back to neutral (1500ms).\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f2\b\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 executeCommand(String cmd)
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl1
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 What it does:
\f1\b0  The master "brain" of the Uno. It interprets the text commands sent over USB from the Raspberry Pi.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Settings Commands:
\f1\b0  Commands like 
\f3\fs26 lim_f:
\f1\fs24 , 
\f3\fs26 lim_r:
\f1\fs24 , and 
\f3\fs26 fs:
\f1\fs24  update the variables in the active memory and immediately write them to the physical EEPROM so they survive power losses.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Calibration (
\f2\fs26 cal_p:
\f0\fs24 ):
\f1\b0  If you send a known battery percentage, it calculates the difference between the physical pin reading and the expected voltage, saving an offset to EEPROM.\
\ls4\ilvl1
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Drive Commands (
\f2\fs26 a
\f0\fs24  and 
\f2\fs26 b
\f0\fs24 ):
\f1\b0  * 
\f3\fs26 a
\f1\fs24  is forward, 
\f3\fs26 b
\f1\fs24  is reverse.\
\pard\tx1660\tx2160\pardeftab720\li2160\fi-2160\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl2\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9642 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 It receives a power level (1-10). It maps this to the ESC pulse ranges (1550-2000 for forward, 1400-1200 for reverse).\
\pard\tx1660\tx2160\pardeftab720\li2160\fi-2160\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl2
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9642 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Failsafe Lockout:
\f1\b0  Before executing a direction change, it checks 
\f3\fs26 millis() - last_rev_time < failsafe_sec
\f1\fs24 . If you try to switch directions faster than the allowed failsafe time, it ignores the command, saving your transmission gears.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 5. Main Loops\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 setup()
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl1\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Initializes the display. Checks EEPROM address 22. If it is not 
\f3\fs26 99
\f1\fs24 , it assumes this is a factory-new Arduino and formats the EEPROM with safe default values (e.g., Failsafe = 3.0s, Max Speed = 1). Calculates the Amp meter zero-point while the motor is off. Attaches the ESC to pin 9.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f2\b\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 loop()
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl1
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Phase Timer:
\f1\b0  Cycles the physical LCD display through different "modes" (IP Address -> Voltage -> Amperage -> Battery % -> Max Speeds) using a timing algorithm.\
\ls5\ilvl1
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Serial Listener:
\f1\b0  Listens to the USB port char-by-char, builds a 
\f3\fs26 String
\f1\fs24 , and feeds it to 
\f3\fs26 executeCommand()
\f1\fs24  when it detects a newline 
\f3\fs26 \\n
\f1\fs24 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa321\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs48 \cf0 \strokec2 \uc0\u9881 \u65039  PART 2: STEER CONTROLLER (ESP8266)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 The ESP8266 is explicitly tasked with steering. Because steering servos draw massive current spikes and require hyper-fast update rates, offloading this from the Arduino prevents brown-outs and keeps steering latency extremely low.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 1. Hardware & Core Variables\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Pin 4 (D2):
\f1\b0  The PWM output pin driving the steering servo.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f2\b\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 ABS_MIN_LEFT
\f0\fs24  & 
\f2\fs26 ABS_MAX_RIGHT
\f0\fs24 :
\f1\b0  The "Iron Walls". The exact angles where your physical steering rack maxes out before the servo binds and burns out.\
\ls6\ilvl0
\f2\b\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 currentCenter
\f0\fs24 :
\f1\b0  The trim offset to ensure the car drives perfectly straight.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 2. EEPROM Memory Functions\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\f2\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 saveToEEPROM()
